One of the waste products that accumulates during cellular respiration is called lactic acid. This is a byproduct of the anaerobic breakdown of glucose in the absence of oxygen, which occurs in muscle cells during intense physical activity. Lactic acid is produced when glucose is broken down in the absence of oxygen to produce energy, and it can build up in the muscles and cause fatigue and soreness. However, the body can convert lactic acid back into glucose during the process of aerobic respiration, which occurs in the presence of oxygen and is the primary method of energy production in most cells.
